    <para id="import-auto-idm1118786048">Figure 1. White curd has separated from the yellow whey after curdling.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm1578268800">Once the curd starts to gel, the cheesemakers cut it up, which allows the whey to come out (Figure 2). Drier cheeses are often cut more to form smaller curds, so more of the moisture comes out. Once the curds are cut, they are stirred and heated to release even more whey and further denature the casein. At this point, the curd is separated from the whey and is salted.  Then the cheese is pressed and eventually becomes the shape and consistency of recognizable cheeses.</para>
