    <para id="import-auto-idm1301438624">Figure 2. Curd being broken up by mixers in industrial scale production. (<link url="https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=246468">https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=246468</link>)</para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm1150745424">Once the cheese is shaped, it may be aged a while, allowing the bacteria and/or fungi in the starter cultures to produce different fermentation products and other flavorings for the cheese (termed ripening).  For instance, for Swiss cheese, <emphasis effect="italics">Propionibacterium</emphasis> create propionic acid via fermentation to give it a nutty flavor. Also, other types of microbes can be added at this later time to the young cheeses to help produce more flavors. Some cheeses are aged for years before serving. However, a small taste of a properly aged Parmesan or Gorgonzola will justify the wait and further help you appreciate the splendor of this process! The major steps in this process are summarized in Figure 3.</para>
